nodes.title:
{
  "description": "The Stamp Act of 1765 initiated a significant taxation crisis, marking the beginning of widespread colonial grievances as colonial leaders viewed it as a direct violation of their fundamental rights as Englishmen.",
  "type": "triggering",
  "date": "1765"
}

{
  "description": "The powerful and unifying principle of 'no taxation without representation' emerged as a central rallying cry, effectively bringing together and consolidating various distinct colonial interests under a common banner against British policies.",
  "type": "intermediate"
}

{
  "description": "Key colonial leaders actively organized and implemented effective forms of resistance against British policies, strategically utilizing established committees of correspondence and widespread economic boycotts to challenge imperial authority.",
  "type": "intermediate"
}

{
  "description": "George Washington's critical strategic decision-making involved deliberately avoiding large-scale, decisive battles against the British, while simultaneously focusing efforts on diligently building and enhancing the overall military capacity of the Continental Army, thereby enabling its survival.",
  "type": "intermediate"
}

{
  "description": "A pivotal military and financial alliance was successfully forged with France, primarily through the skillful negotiations of diplomatic leaders such as Benjamin Franklin, which subsequently provided crucial military and financial support to the American war effort.",
  "type": "intermediate"
}

{
  "description": "The American Revolution of 1776 culminated in the successful establishment of an independent United States, fundamentally driven by the coordinated efforts of effective revolutionary leadership, strategic military actions, and crucial foreign alliances.",
  "type": "outcome",
  "date": "1776"
}

{
  "description": "The American Revolution was fundamentally driven by the emergence of effective revolutionary leadership that successfully mobilized colonial opposition to British taxation policies, transforming scattered grievances into a unified independence movement through strategic vision and organizational capacity.",
  "status": "supported"
}

{
  "description": "Specific military and diplomatic leadership proved decisive in winning the American Revolutionary War by enabling the Continental Army's survival through strategic battlefield decisions and securing crucial foreign military and financial support.",
  "status": "supported"
}

{
  "description": "Without the effective coordination and organizational capacity provided by revolutionary leadership, the diverse colonial population would not have achieved the necessary unity and sustained effort required for a successful revolution and independence.",
  "status": "supported"
}

{
  "description": "Alternative explanations suggesting that only economic grievances or external pressures, without the additional factor of strong leadership and organizational capacity, were sufficient to account for the American Revolution and sustain the eight-year conflict.",
  "status": "refuted"
}

{
  "description": "The text states that key leaders provided strategic vision and organizational capacity to unify colonial grievances.",
  "source": "text",
  "name": "Leaders Provided Strategic Vision and Capacity"
}

{
  "description": "The principle of 'no taxation without representation' became a rallying cry that unified diverse colonial interests.",
  "source": "text",
  "name": "No Taxation Without Representation as Rallying Cry"
}

{
  "description": "The text indicates that leaders organized effective resistance through committees of correspondence and economic boycotts.",
  "source": "text",
  "name": "Leaders Organized Resistance Actions"
}

{
  "description": "The text highlights Washington's strategic decision to avoid major battles and build military capacity to ensure army survival.",
  "source": "text",
  "name": "Washington's Strategy for Army Survival"
}

{
  "description": "The text explicitly states that Benjamin Franklin negotiated the crucial alliance with France, providing military and financial support.",
  "source": "text",
  "name": "Franklin Negotiated French Alliance"
}

{
  "description": "The text presents a counterfactual argument, stating that without effective leadership coordination, colonial unity and a successful revolution would not have been achieved.",
  "source": "text",
  "name": "Counterfactual Absence of Leadership"
}

{
  "description": "The text refutes alternative explanations focused solely on economic grievances or external pressures, stating they fail to account for organizational capacity.",
  "source": "text",
  "name": "Refutation of Alternative Explanations"
}

